    {

        "channelId": "UClzCn8DxRSCuMFv_WfzkcrQ",

          "kind": "youtube#comment",

          "id": "Ugy0OI24XvbrVb_HzGd4AaABAg",
          "snippet": {
            "channelId": "UClzCn8DxRSCuMFv_WfzkcrQ",
            "videoId": "EGt8tAUifao",
            "textDisplay": "LUGGAGE TIPS 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7\u003cbr\u003eTie three or four colored ribbons around the handle to your luggage to warn others that this is NOT  THEIR luggage.  People grab luggage at the turnstile and take it  home before you ever see it.  \u003ca href=\"https://youtu.be/q-gLsegazCs\"\u003ehttps://youtu.be/q-gLsegazCs\u003c/a\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnywhere you put your bag, it could be grabbed in error.  Example:  overhead compartment, unloaded from the bus, at the hotel lobby, at the airport turnstile...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThese ribbons make your luggage different and EASY TO SPOT when the piece is surrounded by 35 other cases unloaded from the bus.  Using 4 ribbons make it immediately different than other cases with 1 ribbon.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eUse 1” wide ribbons 14” long and not longer.  Cut the ends at 45 degrees.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTie the ribbons as a sandwich, as if they were one ribbon.  Use a man’s tie, a half Windsor knot for the best look.  After it is tied on, the total length of the ribbons will be about 5 inches from the handle.  This is too short to catch on anything such as rollers.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eScissor cut trim the ribbons to cascading different lengths after they are tied.  Put a drop of Super Glue at the end. \u003cbr\u003eIf each ribbon is slightly a different length by 1/4” the color layers will all show up no matter how they drape.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYou can see these ribbons from 40 feet away.  \u003cbr\u003ePerhaps tie TWO  handles or RINGS top and side of the case.  \u003cbr\u003eTie using a HALF WINDSOR KNOT to the metal buckle ring of the handle.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eLearn Half Windsor knot tying:\u003cbr\u003eIt is the 2nd example in this video\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://youtu.be/X0yh5rKB9lE\"\u003ehttps://youtu.be/X0yh5rKB9lE\u003c/a\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis knot does not loosen.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePut your phone number on one ribbon using a fine point permanent Sharpie.  \u003cbr\u003eExample:  “Owner 454-333-7878”\u003cbr\u003eNo personal name necessary.\u003cbr\u003eNo address necessary on the ribbon.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eChoose one ribbon with an unusual pattern or fabric to really make it unique.  The 4th ribbon could be black color.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eStand by the output port of the turnstile to reduce the chance of someone else grabbing your piece.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTie your skiies, duffel bag, backpack and what ever else with matching ribbons—even your computer case.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf you are a Travel Agent, you could hot gold stamp one ribbon with your name and phone number.  Send them a set of ribbons, red and blue and BLACK to your customer as a gift.  Record this gift in your database so you don’t duplicate yourself.  \u003cbr\u003eBuy a gold hot embossing machine.  Gold emboss your business name on the BLACK  ribbon.  Put the customer’s name on it if possible.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePleasant color combinations:\u003cbr\u003eRed, white and blue\u003cbr\u003eChartreuse and purple and orange\u003cbr\u003eOrange and light blue\u003cbr\u003eOrange and yellow\u003cbr\u003eGray and pink\u003cbr\u003eGreen and yellow\u003cbr\u003eRed and Green\u003cbr\u003eRed and Gold\u003cbr\u003eLight blue and light green and white\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe 4th ribbon could be white, gray, black, tan\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #2   Take a cell phone picture of the ribbon tied on.  Then another picture of the full luggage piece.  You now have a way to communicate “what it looks like” if someone is tasked with searching for it.  \u003cbr\u003eYou can show this picture to the searcher or attach a picture to your report for lost luggage.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTake this picture outside in direct sun not under neon lights.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #3    Place a strip of colored duct tape on the inside lining to your case.  Put TWO pieces in DIFFERENT places such as INSIDE  a pocket to the case.  If you dare, put your phone number DIRECTLY ON THE FABRIC Liner of the case WITHOUT USING TAPE.  Or, put your name and phone number on this tape.  If all identity is stripped from your case, you have this to show.  If someone steals it and rips off identity tags, you can show the police officer the inside tape...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTo be sneaky about the tape, put your phone number on the STICKY side of the tape.  Nothing is on the surface side of this tape.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #4  \u003cbr\u003ePut your phone number on a 2” x 1/2” piece of fabric or plastic sheet.  Use colored Duct tape, such as black or red or neon, to tape this message to the top side of the handle. This message is under the tape hidden from view.  The lettering does not touch the sticky part.  Wrap it 2-3 times.  Also include Tips 1,2,3 above.  If you need to prove identity of the case,  just unwrap it and show.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #5    ADDING UNIQUENESS\u003cbr\u003eUse 4 ribbons \u003cbr\u003eAdd 1 designer ribbon \u003cbr\u003ecolored duct taped handle \u003cbr\u003estencil SPRAY PAINT  a 2 1/2” stencil letter or number or word or your initials to the suit case exterior surface in addition to using all the other ideas here.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eStencil spray paint a letter to the TOP ribbon.\u003cbr\u003eUse ribbons that are wider or more narrow than 1”.\u003cbr\u003ePut a travel sticker on the case.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #6  WEIGH YOUR OWN\u003cbr\u003eScales accuracy varies at different airports.  If you are even 1 pound over, you pay.  So, regulate yourself.             "textDisplay": "LUGGAGE TIPS 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\u003cbr\u003eTie three or four colored ribbons around the handle to your luggage to warn others that this is not their luggage.  People grab luggage at the turnstile and take it  home before you ever see it.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAnywhere you put your bag, it could be grabbed in error.  Example:  overhead compartment, unloaded from the bus, at the hotel lobby, at the airport turnstile...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThese ribbons make your luggage different and EASY TO SPOT when the piece is surrounded by 35 other cases unloaded from the bus.  Using 4 ribbons make it immediately different than other cases with 1 ribbon.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eUse 1” wide ribbons 14” long and not longer.  Cut the ends at 45 degrees.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTie the ribbons as a sandwich, as if they were one ribbon.  Use a man’s tie, a half Windsor knot for the best look.  After it is tied on, the total length of the ribbons will be about 5 inches from the handle.  This is too short to catch on anything such as rollers.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eScissor cut trim the ribbons to cascading different lengths after they are tied.  Put a drop of Super Glue at the end. \u003cbr\u003eIf each ribbon is slightly a different length by 1/4” the color layers will all show up no matter how they drape.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eYou can see these ribbons from 40 feet away.  \u003cbr\u003ePerhaps tie TWO  handles or RINGS top and side of the case.  \u003cbr\u003eTie using a HALF WINDSOR KNOT to the metal buckle ring of the handle.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eLearn Half Windsor knot tying:\u003cbr\u003eIt is the 2nd example in this video\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://youtu.be/X0yh5rKB9lE\"\u003ehttps://youtu.be/X0yh5rKB9lE\u003c/a\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis knot does not loosen.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePut your phone number on one ribbon using a fine point permanent Sharpie.  \u003cbr\u003eExample:  “Owner 454-333-7878”\u003cbr\u003eNo personal name necessary.\u003cbr\u003eNo address necessary on the ribbon.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eChoose one ribbon with an unusual pattern or fabric to really make it unique.  The 4th ribbon could be black color.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eStand by the output port of the turnstile to reduce the chance of someone else grabbing your piece.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTie your skiies, duffel bag, backpack and what ever else with matching ribbons—even your computer case.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf you are a Travel Agent, you could hot gold stamp one ribbon with your name and phone number.  Send them a set of ribbons, red and blue and BLACK to your customer as a gift.  Record this gift in your database so you don’t duplicate yourself.  \u003cbr\u003eBuy a gold hot embossing machine.  Gold emboss your business name on the BLACK  ribbon.  Put the customer’s name on it if possible.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003ePleasant color combinations:\u003cbr\u003eRed, white and blue\u003cbr\u003eChartreuse and purple and orange\u003cbr\u003eOrange and light blue\u003cbr\u003eOrange and yellow\u003cbr\u003eGray and pink\u003cbr\u003eGreen and yellow\u003cbr\u003eRed and Green\u003cbr\u003eRed and Gold\u003cbr\u003eLight blue and light green and white\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe 4th ribbon could be white, gray, black, tan\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #2   Take a cell phone picture of the ribbon tied on.  Then another picture of the full luggage piece.  You now have a way to communicate “what it looks like” if someone is tasked with searching for it.  \u003cbr\u003eYou can show this picture to the searcher or attach a picture to your report for lost luggage.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTake this picture outside in direct sun not under neon lights.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #3    Place a strip of colored duct tape on the inside lining to your case.  Put TWO pieces in DIFFERENT places such as INSIDE  a pocket to the case.  If you dare, put your phone number DIRECTLY ON THE FABRIC Liner of the case WITHOUT USING TAPE.  Or, put your name and phone number on this tape.  If all identity is stripped from your case, you have this to show.  If someone steals it and rips off identity tags, you can show the police officer the inside tape...\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTo be sneaky about the tape, put your phone number on the STICKY side of the tape.  Nothing is on the surface side of this tape.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #4  \u003cbr\u003ePut your phone number on a 2” x 1/2” piece of fabric or plastic sheet.  Use colored Duct tape, such as black or red or neon, to tape this message to the top side of the handle. This message is under the tape hidden from view.  The lettering does not touch the sticky part.  Wrap it 2-3 times.  Also include Tips 1,2,3 above.  If you need to prove identity of the case,  just unwrap it and show.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #5    ADDING UNIQUENESS\u003cbr\u003e4 ribbons \u003cbr\u003e1 designer ribbon \u003cbr\u003ecolored taped handle \u003cbr\u003estencil SPRAY PAINT  a 2 1/2” stencil letter or number or word or your initials to the suit case exterior surface in addition to using all the other ideas here.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eStencil spray paint a letter to the TOP ribbon.\u003cbr\u003eUse ribbons that are wider or more narrow than 1”.\u003cbr\u003ePut a travel sticker on the case.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eTip #6  WEIGH YOUR OWN\u003cbr\u003eScales accuracy varies at different airports.  If you are even 1 pound over, you pay.  So, regulate yourself.  Found on Ebay, buy a\u003cbr\u003eHAND HELD DIGITAL SCALE\u003cbr\u003eIt is less than $15.\u003cbr\u003e...",
            "textOriginal": "LUGGAGE TIPS 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\nTie three or four colored ribbons around the handle to your luggage to warn others that this is not their luggage. Example:  overhead compartment, unloaded from the bus, at the hotel lobby, at the airport turnstile...\n\nThese ribbons make your luggage different and EASY TO SPOT when the piece is surrounded by 35 other cases unloaded from the bus.  Using 4 ribbons make it immediately different than other cases with 1 ribbon.\n\nUse 1” wide ribbons 14” long and not longer.  Cut the ends at 45 degrees.\n\nTie the ribbons as a sandwich, as if they were one ribbon.  Use a man’s tie, a half Windsor knot for the best look.  After it is tied on, the total length of the ribbons will be about 5 inches from the handle.  This is too short to catch on anything such as rollers.\n\nScissor cut trim the ribbons to cascading different lengths after they are tied.  Put a drop of Super Glue at the end. \nIf each ribbon is slightly a different length by 1/4” the color layers will all show up no matter how they drape.  \n\nYou can see these ribbons from 40 feet away.  \nPerhaps tie TWO  handles or RINGS top and side of the case.  \nTie using a HALF WINDSOR KNOT to the metal buckle ring of the handle.  \n\nLearn Half Windsor knot tying:\nIt is the 2nd example in this video\nhttps://youtu.be/X0yh5rKB9lE\nThis knot does not loosen.\n\nPut your phone number on one ribbon using a fine point permanent Sharpie.  \nExample:  “Owner 454-333-7878”\nNo personal name necessary.\nNo address necessary on the ribbon.\n\nChoose one ribbon with an unusual pattern or fabric to really make it unique.  The 4th ribbon could be black color.\n\nStand by the output port of the turnstile to reduce the chance of someone else grabbing your piece.\n\nTie your skiies, duffel bag, backpack and what ever else with matching ribbons—even your computer case.\n\nIf you are a Travel Agent, you could hot gold stamp one ribbon with your name and phone number.  Send them a set of ribbons, red and blue and BLACK to your customer as a gift.  Record this gift in your database so you don’t duplicate yourself.  \nBuy a gold hot embossing machine.  Gold emboss your business name on the BLACK  ribbon.  Put the customer’s name on it if possible.\n\nPleasant color combinations:\nRed, white and blue\nChartreuse and purple and orange\nOrange and light blue\nOrange and yellow\nGray and pink\nGreen and yellow\nRed and Green\nRed and Gold\nLight blue and light green and white\n\nThe 4th ribbon could be white, gray, black, tan\n\nTip #2   Take a cell phone picture of the ribbon tied on.  Then another picture of the full luggage piece.  You now have a way to communicate “what it looks like” if someone is tasked with searching for it.  \nYou can show this picture to the searcher or attach a picture to your report for lost luggage.  \n\nTake this picture outside in direct sun not under neon lights.\n\nTip #3    Place a strip of colored duct tape on the inside lining to your case.  Put TWO pieces in DIFFERENT places such as INSIDE  a pocket to the case.  If you dare, put your phone number DIRECTLY ON THE FABRIC Liner of the case WITHOUT USING TAPE.  Or, put your name and phone number on this tape.  If all identity is stripped from your case, you have this to show.  If someone steals it and rips off identity tags, you can show the police officer the inside tape...\n\nTo be sneaky about the tape, put your phone number on the STICKY side of the tape.  Nothing is on the surface side of this tape.\n\nTip #4  \nPut your phone number on a 2” x 1/2” piece of fabric or plastic sheet.  Use colored Duct tape, such as black or red or neon, to tape this message to the top side of the handle. This message is under the tape hidden from view.  The lettering does not touch the sticky part.  Wrap it 2-3 times.  Also include Tips 1,2,3 above.  If you need to prove identity of the case,  just unwrap it and show.\n\nTip #5    ADDING UNIQUENESS\n4 ribbons \n1 designer ribbon \ncolored taped handle \nstencil SPRAY PAINT  a 2 1/2” stencil letter or number or word or your initials to the suit case exterior surface in addition to using all the other ideas here.\n\nStencil spray paint a letter to the TOP ribbon.\nUse ribbons that are wider or more narrow than 1”.\nPut a travel sticker on the case.\n\nTip #6  WEIGH YOUR OWN\nScales accuracy varies at different airports.  If you are even 1 pound over, you pay.  So, regulate yourself.  Found on Ebay, buy a\nHAND HELD DIGITAL SCALE\nIt is less than $15.\n...",

            "textOriginal": "LUGGAGE TIPS 1, 2, 3\nTie two or three colored ribbons around the handle to your luggage to warn others that this is not their luggage.  People grab luggage at the turnstile and take it  home before you ever see it.\n\nAnywhere you put your bag, it could be grabbed in error.  Example:  overhead compartment, unloaded from the bus, at the hotel lobby, at the airport turnstile...\n\nThese ribbons make your luggage different and EASY TO SPOT when the piece is surrounded by 35 other cases unloaded from the bus.\n\nUse 1” wide ribbons 14” long and not longer.  Cut the ends at 45 degrees.\nScissor cut trim the ribbons to cascading different lengths after they are tied.  Put a drop of Super Glue at the end. \nIf each ribbon is slightly a different length by 1/4” the color layers will all show up no matter how they drape.  \n\nTie the 3 ribbons as a sandwich, as if they were one ribbon.  Use a man’s tie, a half Windsor knot for the best look.  After it is tied on, the total length of the ribbons will be about 5 inches from the handle.  This is too short to catch on anything. \nHalf Windsor knot tying\nhttps://youtu.be/S_ny-hrKqzU\n\nYou can see this ribbon from 40 feet away.  Perhaps tie TWO  handles or RINGS top and side of the case.  This way, it won’t slide around.  This knot does not loosen.\n\nPut your phone number on one ribbon using a permanent Sharpie.  \nExample:  “Owner 454-333-7878”\nNo personal name necessary.\nNo address necessary on the ribbon.\n\nChoose one ribbon with an unusual pattern or fabric to really make it unique.\n\nStand by the output port of the turnstile to reduce the chance of someone else grabbing your piece.\n\nTie your skiies, duffel bag, backpack and what ever else with matching ribbons—even your computer case.\n\nIf you are a Travel Agent, you could hot gold stamp one ribbon with your name and phone number.  Send them a set of ribbons, red and blue and BLACK to your customer as a gift.  Record this gift in your database so you don’t duplicate yourself.  \nBuy a gold hot embossing machine.  Gold emboss your business name on the BLACK  ribbon. Then another picture of the full luggage piece.  You now have a way to communicate “what it looks like” if someone is tasked with searching for it.  Take this picture outside in direct sun.\n\nTip #3    Place a strip of colored duct tape on the inside lining to your case.  Put your name and phone number on this tape. Instead, at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pj86MB7p5OU&t=9m21s\"\u003e9:21\u003c/a\u003e, the FAA's military liaison at Boston Centre passed on information that American 11 was still in the air, hijacked and heading south towards the capital (the 9/11 Commission — according to page 26 of their Report — were, "unable to identify the source of this mistaken FAA information"). Langley's alert fighters scrambled at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pj86MB7p5OU&t=9m23s\"\u003e9:23\u003c/a\u003e and radar data shows them airborne by \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pj86MB7p5OU&t=9m30s\"\u003e9:30\u003c/a\u003e. Scrambled with no target instructions, however, the fighters followed their generic flight plan (090 for 60) and vectored east out to sea leaving Washington undefended as American 77 closed in. \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAn unidentified blip appeared on radar screens at Washington Dulles Airport at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pj86MB7p5OU&t=9m32s\"\u003e9:32\u003c/a\u003e. The target was 12-14 miles southwest and moving at high speed towards P-56 (the prohibited airspace around the White House and Capitol Building). Secret Service personnel hustled Vice President Dick Cheney into the White House command bunker and staff were ordered to evacuate the building. Chaos erupted over at the Capitol when news of an incoming plane spread like wildfire and terrified congressional officials and their staff crowded into hallways, elevators and stairwells in a desperate bid to escape. Arlington dispatch received an excited call from police officer Richard Cox at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pj86MB7p5OU&t=9m35s\"\u003e9:35\u003c/a\u003e. "It's an American Airlines plane, heading east down over the pike," his voice crackled, "possibly towards the Pentagon." Father Stephen McGraw, a Catholic priest stuck in heavy traffic on the Pentagon exit to Washington Boulevard, stared in disbelief as American 77 thundered overhead toppling a light pole and injuring a taxi driver. A moment later, the jetliner smashed into the concrete façade of the Pentagon and exploded as it disappeared into the wall. "I saw it crash into the building," said McGraw. "There was an explosion and a loud noise, and I felt the impact." (Bamford, 47-8). The bodies of Flight 77 passengers and crew, as well as Pentagon employees, would be painstakingly recovered from the rubble in the days and weeks that followed. With Langley's alert fighters over a hundred miles away, Andrews Air Force Base (situated just outside Washington) scrambled fighters "weapons-free" to protect the capital at the request of the Secret Service. In fact, protecting the Washington DC area is part of the charter of the 113th Air National Guard Wing stationed at Andrews: "as part of its dual mission, the 113th provides capable and ready response forces for the District of Columbia in the event of a natural disaster or civil emergency."             "videoId": "Mpc2OuJPOog",
            "textDisplay": "An airline pilot can instantly send a hijack alert by a number of methods, including a button on the joystick. On 9/11 four airliners went rogue yet none of the eight pilots sent an alert.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFlight 11, Boston—LA, diverted N shortly after take-off and, at the edge of a large "radar corridor" (an area beyond FAA and NORAD mechanical radar coverage), the on-board transponder (which sends flight data such as identity, altitude, and GPS position to air-traffic control) was switched off.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe plane then reappeared on radar, turned SE, and crossed paths with Flight 175, Boston—LA, before going on to hit the North Tower of the World Trade Centre at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=8m46s\"\u003e8:46\u003c/a\u003e (a flash of light glinted from the plane's nose a split second before impact). Flight 175 continued SW until, at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=8m47s\"\u003e8:47\u003c/a\u003e, it passed in close proximity to Flight 93, Newark—San Francisco, whose take-off had been delayed by 25 minutes. Just before the closest point of approach 175's transponder was switched off, the plane then swung around and flew NE to hit the South Tower at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m03s\"\u003e9:03\u003c/a\u003e (another ray of light shone from the plane's nose a split second before it hit its target). Flight 93, after diverting N to meet 175, proceeded W at cruising altitude and entered a large radar hole near Cleveland.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eFlight 77, Washington DC—LA, flew 300 W after take-off passing through a substantial N-S radar corridor over W Virginia. 77 turned, its transponder was switched off, and it re-entered radar darkness heading E.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe plane then appeared on radar, flew all the way back to DC and looped to hit the newly renovated, reinforced west wedge of the Pentagon at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m37s\"\u003e9:37\u003c/a\u003e killing a number of accountants and destroying their paperwork (all CCTV footage of the impact was then seized by the FBI and has never been released).\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eAfter flying W for 45 minutes Flight 95 was finally warned — by a United dispatcher acting on his own initiative — "Beware any cockpit intrusion" (\u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m23s\"\u003e9:23\u003c/a\u003e-24). Three minutes later the first spurious cellphone call (from 35,000 ft) was received, "Our plane has been hijacked ... call the authorities" (the resultant 9-1-1 calls would help establish the 93 crash site as an FBI crime scene). At \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m27s\"\u003e9:27\u003c/a\u003e the pilot replied, "Ed, confirm latest message please — Jason". One minute later 93 dropped 700 ft and the pilot yelled over the radio "Mayday" and "Hey get out of here, get out of here — get out of here" (no formal hijack alert was sent). At \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m32s\"\u003e9:32\u003c/a\u003e air-traffic control were informed, "We have a bomb on board". The jetliner turned S. A flight attendant contacted UA by Airfone at \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m36s\"\u003e9:36\u003c/a\u003e and notified them of the hijacking. At \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=9m39s\"\u003e9:39\u003c/a\u003e air-traffic control were warned once again "We have a bomb aboard". With its hijack status clearly established 93's transponder was switched off and it re-entered radar darkness heading for Washington DC. Incredibly, the Defence Department claim that they were unaware of Flight 93 until \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mpc2OuJPOog&t=10m07s\"\u003e10:07\u003c/a\u003e — one minute after the 9/11 attack.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"An aircraft at Eglin AFB would be painted and numbered as an exact duplicate for a civil registered aircraft belonging to a CIA proprietary organization in the Miami area. At a designated time the duplicate would be substituted for the actual civil aircraft ... The actual registered aircraft would be converted to a drone.... From the rendezvous point the passenger-carrying aircraft will descend to minimum altitude and go directly into an auxiliary field at Eglin AFB ... When over Cuba the drone will begin transmitting on the international distress frequency a 'MAY DAY' message stating he is under attack by Cuban MIG aircraft." Department of Defence, Operation Northwoods, March 1962\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDrafted by the Joint Chiefs of Staff and submitted to Defence Secretary Robert McNamara on 13 March 1962, the DOD's Top Secret Operation Northwoods proposal — for false flag attacks on American civilian and military targets to be used as the pretext for a war on Cuba — was rejected by President John F Kennedy. Among the possible scenarios outlined in "brief but precise" detail was a fiendish plane-swap deception involving the replacement of a "chartered civil airliner" with an exact duplicate. Passengers would board the mock-up at a regular airport and the plane would take off as normal. The original registered aircraft would be converted to a drone at a secret-state facility. At a pre-planned position the two would rendezvous, the piloted aircraft — carrying a black-ops team "boarded under carefully prepared aliases" — would descend below radar and head to an "auxiliary field" at a nearby Air Force base. The original airliner, under remote control, would continue along the duplicate's flight path until, at a suitable location, it would be blown out of the sky by "Cuban MIGs" (i.e. on-board explosives remotely detonated). Retrieved in 1997 under Freedom of Information laws by a federal agency dealing with documents related to the assassination of President Kennedy, the Defence Department's preliminary Northwoods proposal — "suitable for planning purposes" — also recommended planting aircraft debris and phoney evidence at crash sites and called for the development of a "Communist Cuban terror campaign" within US cities to be blamed on Cuban agents and refugees.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e"three males appearing to be Iranian ... dark-skinned with red bandanas on their heads ... two in the cockpit and a third had a red belt with a box that constituted some kind of a bomb." A synthesized cellphone call from Flight 93 ("Cellphones don't work at five or six miles of altitude. That's why airlines were only introducing pico-cell technology to enable them to do so in 2006/7", Rowland Morgan, Flight 93 Revealed) \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eDuring a 2004 Christmas Eve address to US forces in Baghdad Defence Secretary Donald Rumsfeld actually said: "the people who attacked the United States in New York, shot down the plane over Pennsylvania." The one eyewitness to 93's ostensible "crash" was Lee Purbaugh, a scrap-metal worker hired only the day before: "I saw it rock from side to side then, suddenly, it dipped and dived, nose first, with a huge explosion, into the ground." According to the 9/11 Commission Report — based on flight data supplied by the Pentagon and FBI — 93 supposedly rolled over at 580 mph and then "crashed" upside down. Three "loud bangs" were heard and 12 witnesses reported seeing an unmarked white fighter-jet circling overhead. A C-130 cargo plane was also seen and is officially acknowledged to have been in the area. Several boxes of "surprisingly intact mementos of lives lost" were recovered from the Shanksville crater site and main Indian Lake debris field some 3 miles to the east (a hijacker's Lebanese passport and Cripps-style red bandana were also retrieved). The Type-Rating training on the Airbus A-320 covers the purpose and functionality of the Ditch Switch - and this is something that every pilot trained on the A-320 should have \"burned into their minds\" to the point where they would \"automatically\" know to flip this switch on prior to an emergency water landing - without having to be reminded to do it by reading a checklist.  Pilot Proficiency is all about thoroughly learning, knowing and mastering every operational feature and aspect of each and every aircraft that a pilot is certified to fly and in this particular instance, there was an ominous lacking in proficiency on behalf of both pilots in their  failure to turn on the Ditch Switch before landing their A-320 in the Hudson River.  But despite this lacking of proficiency,  the overall outcome was still exceptional as the crew did get everything else done very well and everyone on board survived.  It would have been a perfect scenario without the ice-cold water rushing into the cabin - a problem that was made even worse than it should have been - not only by the crew's failure to turn on the Ditch Switch before the belly-landing on the waterbut also after the ditching when a passenger - who didn't pay attention to the pre-flight safety briefing - opened one of the doors in the rear of the  aircraft, causing water to flood into the cabin.  The safety-information cards in each seatback pocket (which the passengers are informed about during the pre-flight safety briefing) clearly state not to open the rear emergency escape doors in the event of a water landing - because the tail of the plane will settle too deeply into the water to allow the rear emergency doors to be safely opened without flooding the cabin with water.  Here again is a shortcoming of the flight crew and in this case  - it was the flight attendants - who after the ditching failed to emphatically warn the passengers who were sitting by the rear emergency escape doors not to open those doors.",
